# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: quantum-chemistry-dft
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/configuration-interaction] where Ψ is usually the electronic ground state of the system.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/configuration-interaction] If the expansion includes all possible CSFs of the appropriate symmetry, then this is a full configuration interaction procedure which exactly solves the electronic Schrödinger equation within the space spanned by the one-particle basis set.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/configuration-interaction] The first term in the above expansion is normally the Hartree–Fock determinant.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/configuration-interaction] The other CSFs can be characterised by the number of spin orbitals that are swapped with virtual orbitals from the Hartree–Fock determinant.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/configuration-interaction] If only one spin orbital differs, we describe this as a single excitation determinant.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/configuration-interaction] If two spin orbitals differ it is a double excitation determinant and so on.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/configuration-interaction] This is used to limit the number of determinants in the expansion which is called the CI-space.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/configuration-interaction] Truncating the CI-space is important to save computational time.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/configuration-interaction] For example, the method CID is limited to double excitations only.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/configuration-interaction] The method CISD is limited to single and double excitations.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/configuration-interaction] Single excitations on their own do not mix with the Hartree–Fock determinant (see Brillouin's theorem).
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/configuration-interaction] These methods, CID and CISD, are in many standard programs.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/configuration-interaction] The Davidson correction can be used to estimate a correction to the CISD energy to account for higher excitations.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/configuration-interaction] An important problem of truncated CI methods is their size-inconsistency which means the energy of two infinitely separated particles is not double the energy of the single particle.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/configuration-interaction] Slater determinants are constructed from sets of orthonormal spin orbitals, so that $\left\langle \Phi _{i}^{SO}|\Phi _{j}^{SO}\right\rangle =\delta _{ij}$ , making $\mathbb {S}$ the identity matrix and simplifying the above matrix equation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/configuration-interaction] The solution of the CI procedure are some eigenvalues $\mathbf {E} ^{j}$ and their corresponding eigenvectors $\mathbf {c} _{I}^{j}$ .
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/configuration-interaction] The eigenvalues are the energies of the ground and some electronically excited states.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/configuration-interaction] By this it is possible to calculate energy differences (excitation energies) with CI methods.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/configuration-interaction] Excitation energies of truncated CI methods are generally too high, because the excited states are not that well correlated as the ground state is.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/configuration-interaction] For equally (balanced) correlation of ground and excited states (better excitation energies) one can use more than one reference determinant from which all singly, doubly, ... excited determinants are included (multireference configuration interaction).
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/configuration-interaction] MRCI also gives better correlation of the ground state which is important if it has more than one dominant determinant.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/configuration-interaction] This can be easily understood because some higher excited determinants are also taken into the CI-space.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/configuration-interaction] For nearly degenerate determinants which build the ground state one should use the multi-configurational self-consistent field (MCSCF) method because the Hartree–Fock determinant is qualitatively wrong and so are the CI wave functions and energies.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] The method was initially developed by Fritz Coester and Hermann Kümmel in the 1950s for studying nuclear-physics phenomena, but became more frequently used when in 1966 Jiří Čížek (and later together with Josef Paldus) reformulated the method for electron correlation in atoms and molecules.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] It is now one of the most prevalent methods in quantum chemistry that includes electronic correlation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] CC theory is simply the perturbative variant of the many-electron theory (MET) of Oktay Sinanoğlu, which is the exact (and variational) solution of the many-electron problem, so it was also called "coupled-pair MET (CPMET)".
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] J. Čížek used the correlation function of MET and used Goldstone-type perturbation theory to get the energy expression, while original MET was completely variational. Čížek first developed the linear CPMET and then generalized it to full CPMET in the same work in 1966.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] He then also performed an application of it on the benzene molecule with Sinanoğlu in the same year.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] Because MET is somewhat difficult to perform computationally, CC is simpler and thus, in today's computational chemistry, CC is the best variant of MET and gives highly accurate results in comparison to experiments.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] where H is the Hamiltonian of the system, $|\Psi \rangle$ is the exact wavefunction, and *E* is the exact energy of the ground state.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] Coupled-cluster theory can also be used to obtain solutions for excited states using, for example, linear-response, equation-of-motion, state-universal multi-reference, or valence-universal multi-reference coupled cluster approaches.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] where $|\Phi _{0}\rangle$ is the reference wave function, which is typically a Slater determinant constructed from Hartree–Fock molecular orbitals, though other wave functions such as configuration interaction, multi-configurational self-consistent field, or Brueckner orbitals can also be used.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] T is the cluster operator, which, when acting on $|\Phi _{0}\rangle$ , produces a linear combination of excited determinants from the reference wave function (see section below for greater detail).
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] The choice of the exponential ansatz is opportune because (unlike other ansatzes, for example, configuration interaction) it guarantees the size extensivity of the solution.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] Size consistency in CC theory, also unlike other theories, does not depend on the size consistency of the reference wave function.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] If one were to use, for example, the CCSD, or CCSD(T) levels of theory, they would not provide reasonable results for the bond breaking of F2, with the latter one approaches unphysical potential energy surfaces, though this is for reasons other than just size consistency.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] A criticism of the method is that the conventional implementation employing the similarity-transformed Hamiltonian (see below) is not variational, though there are bi-variational and quasi-variational approaches that have been developed since the first implementations of the theory.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] where $T_{1}$ is the operator of all single excitations, $T_{2}$ is the operator of all double excitations, and so forth.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] In the above formulae ${\hat {a}}^{a}={\hat {a}}_{a}^{\dagger }$ and ${\hat {a}}_{i}$ denote the creation and annihilation operators respectively, while *i*, *j* stand for occupied (hole) and *a*, *b* for unoccupied (particle) orbitals (states).
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] The creation and annihilation operators in the coupled-cluster terms above are written in canonical form, where each term is in the normal order form, with respect to the Fermi vacuum $|\Phi _{0}\rangle$ .
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] Applying the exponential cluster operator to the wave function, one can then generate more than doubly excited determinants due to the various powers of $T_{1}$ and $T_{2}$ that appear in the resulting expressions (see below).
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] Solving for the unknown coefficients $t_{a}^{i}$ and $t_{ab}^{ij}$ is necessary for finding the approximate solution $|\Psi \rangle$ .
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] Often, as was done above, the cluster operator includes only singles and doubles (see CCSD below) as this offers a computationally affordable method that performs better than MP2 and CISD, but is not very accurate usually.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] For double-bond breaking and more complicated problems in chemistry, quadruple excitations often become important as well, though usually they have small contributions for most problems, and as such, the contribution of $T_{5}$ , $T_{6}$ etc. to the operator T is typically small.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] where there are a total of *q* coefficients (*t*-amplitudes) to solve for.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] the latter being the equations to be solved, and the former the equation for the evaluation of the energy.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] The subscript *C* designates the connected part of the corresponding operator expression.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] The resulting equations are a set of non-linear equations, which are solved in an iterative manner.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] Standard quantum-chemistry packages (GAMESS (US), NWChem, ACES II, etc.) solve the coupled-cluster equations using the Jacobi method and direct inversion of the iterative subspace (DIIS) extrapolation of the *t*-amplitudes to accelerate convergence.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] The classification of traditional coupled-cluster methods rests on the highest number of excitations allowed in the definition of T .
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] Q – for quadruple excitations (*quadruples*).
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] Terms in round brackets indicate that these terms are calculated based on perturbation theory.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] An estimate to the connected triples contribution is calculated non-iteratively using many-body perturbation theory arguments.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] The complexity of equations and the corresponding computer codes, as well as the cost of the computation, increases sharply with the highest level of excitation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] For many applications CCSD, while relatively inexpensive, does not provide sufficient accuracy except for the smallest systems (approximately 2 to 4 electrons), and often an approximate treatment of triples is needed.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] The most well known coupled-cluster method that provides an estimate of connected triples is CCSD(T), which provides a good description of closed-shell molecules near the equilibrium geometry, but breaks down in more complicated situations such as bond breaking and diradicals.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] Another popular method that makes up for the failings of the standard CCSD(T) approach is CR-CC(2,3), where the triples contribution to the energy is computed from the difference between the exact solution and the CCSD energy and is not based on perturbation-theory arguments.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] More complicated coupled-cluster methods such as CCSDT and CCSDTQ are used only for high-accuracy calculations of small molecules.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] The inclusion of all *n* levels of excitation for the *n*-electron system gives the exact solution of the Schrödinger equation within the given basis set, within the Born–Oppenheimer approximation (although schemes have also been drawn up to work without the BO approximation).
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] One possible improvement to the standard coupled-cluster approach is to add terms linear in the interelectronic distances through methods such as CCSD-R12.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] This improves the treatment of dynamical electron correlation by satisfying the Kato cusp condition and accelerates convergence with respect to the orbital basis set.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] Unfortunately, R12 methods invoke the resolution of the identity, which requires a relatively large basis set in order to be a good approximation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] The coupled-cluster method described above is also known as the *single-reference* (SR) coupled-cluster method because the exponential ansatz involves only one reference function $|\Phi _{0}\rangle$ .
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] Josef Paldus also wrote his first-hand account of the origins of coupled-cluster theory, its implementation, and exploitation in electronic wave-function determination; his account is primarily about the making of coupled-cluster theory rather than about the theory itself.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] Paldus, in *Methods in Computational Molecular Physics*, Vol.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] 293 of *Nato Advanced Study Institute Series B: Physics*, edited by S.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] If all of the nonlinear terms in $e^{S}$ are included, then the SAC equations become equivalent to the standard coupled-cluster equations of Jiří Čížek.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] This is due to the cancellation of the energy-dependent terms with the disconnected terms contributing to the product of $He^{S}$ , resulting in the same set of nonlinear energy-independent equations.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] Typically, all nonlinear terms, except ${\tfrac {1}{2}}S_{2}^{2}$ are dropped, as higher-order nonlinear terms are usually small.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] In nuclear physics, coupled cluster saw significantly less use than in quantum chemistry during the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] More powerful computers, as well as advances in theory (such as the inclusion of three-nucleon interactions), have spawned renewed interest in the method since then, and it has been successfully applied to neutron-rich and medium-mass nuclei.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/coupled-cluster] Coupled cluster is one of several ab initio methods in nuclear physics and is specifically suitable for nuclei having closed or nearly closed shells.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] Within the Hartree–Fock method of quantum chemistry, the antisymmetric wave function is approximated by a single Slater determinant.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] Exact wave functions, however, cannot generally be expressed as single determinants.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] The single-determinant approximation does not take into account Coulomb correlation, leading to a total electronic energy different from the exact solution of the non-relativistic Schrödinger equation within the Born–Oppenheimer approximation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] Therefore, the Hartree–Fock limit is always above this exact energy.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] The difference is called the *correlation energy*, a term coined by Löwdin.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] The concept of the correlation energy was studied earlier by Wigner.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] A certain amount of electron correlation is already considered within the HF approximation, found in the electron exchange term describing the correlation between electrons with parallel spin.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] This basic correlation prevents two parallel-spin electrons from being found at the same point in space and is often called Pauli correlation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] Coulomb correlation, on the other hand, describes the correlation between the spatial position of electrons due to their Coulomb repulsion, and is responsible for chemically important effects such as London dispersion.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] There is also a correlation related to the overall symmetry or total spin of the considered system.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] The word correlation energy has to be used with caution.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] First it is usually defined as the energy difference of a correlated method relative to the Hartree–Fock energy.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] But this is not the full correlation energy because some correlation is already included in HF.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] Secondly the correlation energy is highly dependent on the basis set used.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] The "exact" energy is the energy with full correlation and complete basis set.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] Electron correlation is sometimes divided into dynamical and non-dynamical (static) correlation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] Dynamical correlation is the correlation of the movement of electrons and is described under electron correlation dynamics and also with the configuration interaction (CI) method.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] Static correlation is important for molecules whose ground state is well described only with more than one (nearly) degenerate determinant.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] In this case the Hartree–Fock wavefunction (only one determinant) is qualitatively wrong.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] The multi-configurational self-consistent field (MCSCF) method takes account of this static correlation, but not dynamical correlation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] If one wants to calculate excitation energies (energy differences between the ground and excited states) one has to be careful that both states are equally balanced (e.g., Multireference configuration interaction).
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] In simple terms, the molecular orbitals of the Hartree–Fock method are optimized by evaluating the energy of an electron in each molecular orbital moving in the mean field of all other electrons, rather than including the instantaneous repulsion between electrons.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] One of the most important methods for correcting for the missing correlation is the configuration interaction (CI) method.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] Starting with the Hartree–Fock wavefunction as the ground determinant, one takes a linear combination of the ground and excited determinants $\Phi _{I}$ as the correlated wavefunction and optimizes the weighting factors $c_{I}$ according to the Variational Principle.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] When taking all possible excited determinants, one speaks of Full-CI.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] In a Full-CI wavefunction all electrons are fully correlated.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] For non-small molecules, Full-CI is much too computationally expensive.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] One truncates the CI expansion and gets well-correlated wavefunctions and well-correlated energies according to the level of truncation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] Perturbation theory gives correlated energies, but no new wavefunctions.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] This means the calculated energy is not an upper bound for the exact energy.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] It is possible to partition Møller–Plesset perturbation theory energies via Interacting Quantum Atoms (IQA) energy partitioning (although most commonly the correlation energy is not partitioned).
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] This is an extension to the theory of Atoms in Molecules.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] IQA energy partitioning enables one to look in detail at the correlation energy contributions from individual atoms and atomic interactions.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] IQA correlation energy partitioning has also been shown to be possible with coupled cluster methods.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] Examples for those combinations are CASPT2 and SORCI.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] This approach includes a term depending on interelectron distance into wavefunction.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] This leads to faster convergence in terms of basis set size than pure gaussian-type basis set, but requires calculation of more complex integrals.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] To simplify them, interelectron distances are expanded into a series making for simpler integrals.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] The idea of R12 methods is quite old, but practical implementations begun to appear only recently.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] In condensed matter physics, electrons are typically described with reference to a periodic lattice of atomic nuclei.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] Non-interacting electrons are therefore typically described by Bloch waves, which correspond to the delocalized, symmetry adapted molecular orbitals used in molecules (while Wannier functions correspond to localized molecular orbitals).
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] A number of important theoretical approximations have been proposed to explain electron correlations in these crystalline systems.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] The Fermi liquid model of correlated electrons in metals is able to explain the temperature dependence of resistivity by electron-electron interactions.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] It also forms the basis for the BCS theory of superconductivity, which is the result of phonon-mediated electron-electron interactions.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] Systems that escape a Fermi liquid description are said to be **strongly-correlated**.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] In them, interactions plays such an important role that qualitatively new phenomena emerge.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] This is the case, for example, when the electrons are close to a metal-insulator transition.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] The Hubbard model is based on the tight-binding approximation, and can explain conductor-insulator transitions in Mott insulators such as transition metal oxides by the presence of repulsive Coulombic interactions between electrons.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] Its one-dimensional version is considered an archetype of the strong-correlations problem and displays many dramatic manifestations such as quasi-particle fractionalization.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] However, there is no exact solution of the Hubbard model in more than one dimension.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] The RKKY interaction can explain electron spin correlations between unpaired inner shell electrons in different atoms in a conducting crystal by a second-order interaction that is mediated by conduction electrons.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] The Tomonaga–Luttinger liquid model approximates second order electron-electron interactions as bosonic interactions.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] where *ρ*(**r***a*,**r***b*) represents the joint electronic density, or the probability density of finding electron *a* at **r***a* and electron *b* at **r***b*.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] Within this notation, *ρ*(**r***a*,**r***b*) *d***r***a* *d***r***b* represents the probability of finding the two electrons in their respective volume elements *d***r***a* and *d***r***b*.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] If these two electrons are correlated, then the probability of finding electron *a* at a certain position in space depends on the position of electron *b*, and vice versa.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] In other words, the product of their independent density functions does not adequately describe the real situation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electron-correlation] At small distances, the uncorrelated pair density is too large; at large distances, the uncorrelated pair density is too small (i.e. the electrons tend to "avoid each other").
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] Quantum chemistry studies focus on the electronic ground state and excited states of atoms, molecules, and ions.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] Such calculations allow chemical reactions to be described with respect to pathways, intermediates, and transition states.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] Spectroscopic properties may also be predicted.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] Typically, such studies assume the electronic wave function is adiabatically parameterized by the nuclear positions (i.e., the Born–Oppenheimer approximation).
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] A wide variety of approaches are used, including semi-empirical methods, density functional theory, Hartree–Fock calculations, quantum Monte Carlo methods, and coupled cluster methods.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] Understanding electronic structure and molecular dynamics through the development of computational solutions to the Schrödinger equation is a central goal of quantum chemistry.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] Some view the birth of quantum chemistry as starting with the discovery of the Schrödinger equation and its application to the hydrogen atom.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] However, a 1927 article of Walter Heitler (1904–1981) and Fritz London, is often recognized as the first milestone in the history of quantum chemistry.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] This was the first application of quantum mechanics to the diatomic hydrogen molecule, and thus to the phenomenon of the chemical bond.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] Prior to this, a critical conceptual framework was provided by Gilbert N.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] Lewis in his 1916 paper *The Atom and the Molecule*, wherein Lewis developed the first working model of valence electrons.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] Important contributions were also made by Yoshikatsu Sugiura and S.C.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] A series of articles by Linus Pauling, written throughout the 1930s, integrated the work of Heitler, London, Sugiura, Wang, Lewis, and John C.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] Slater on the concept of valence and its quantum-mechanical basis into a new theoretical framework.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] The work soon became a standard text at many universities.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] In 1937, Hans Hellmann appears to have been the first to publish a book on quantum chemistry, in the Russian and German languages.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] In the years to follow, this theoretical basis slowly began to be applied to chemical structure, reactivity, and bonding.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] In addition to the investigators mentioned above, important progress and critical contributions were made in the early years of this field by Irving Langmuir, Robert S.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] Robert Oppenheimer, Hans Hellmann, Maria Goeppert Mayer, Erich Hückel, Douglas Hartree, John Lennard-Jones, and Vladimir Fock.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] The **electronic structure** of an atom or molecule is the quantum state of its electrons.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] The first step in solving a quantum chemical problem is usually solving the Schrödinger equation (or Dirac equation in relativistic quantum chemistry) with the electronic molecular Hamiltonian, usually making use of the Born–Oppenheimer (B–O) approximation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] This is called determining the electronic structure of the molecule.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] An exact solution for the non-relativistic Schrödinger equation can only be obtained for the hydrogen atom (though exact solutions for the bound state energies of the hydrogen molecular ion within the B-O approximation have been identified in terms of the generalized Lambert W function).
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] Since all other atomic and molecular systems involve the motions of three or more "particles", their Schrödinger equations cannot be solved analytically and so approximate and/or computational solutions must be sought.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] The process of seeking computational solutions to these problems is part of the field known as computational chemistry.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] As mentioned above, Heitler and London's method was extended by Slater and Pauling to become the valence-bond (VB) method.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] In this method, attention is primarily devoted to the pairwise interactions between atoms, and this method therefore correlates closely with classical chemists' drawings of bonds.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] It focuses on how the atomic orbitals of an atom combine to give individual chemical bonds when a molecule is formed, incorporating the two key concepts of orbital hybridization and resonance.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] A covalent bond is formed when there is an overlap of half-filled atomic orbitals from two atoms, which together form an electron pair.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] The strength and energy of the system is dependent on the amount of overlap.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] As the atoms move together, their orbitals start to overlap and the electrons begin to feel the attraction of both nuclei.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] There is also a repulsion that begins to occur, which becomes very strong when the atoms are too close together.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] The ideal and most stable length between the two atoms is the bond distance, which is when the repulsive and attractive forces balance resulting in the lowest energy configuration.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] Orientation of the orbitals can have a large affect on what bonds are formed, including if any is formed.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] When there is a direct overlap of one atomic orbital from each atom, a sigma (σ) bond is formed.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] This can be created from two s-orbitals, an s-orbital and a p-orbital, or two p-orbitals.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] A pi (π) bond is formed from a side-to-side overlap of two p-orbitals.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] The pi bond only forms if the phases of the overlapping p-orbitals are the same.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] An alternative approach to valence bond theory was developed in 1929 by Friedrich Hund and Robert S.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] Mulliken, in which electrons are described by mathematical functions delocalized over an entire molecule.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] The Hund–Mulliken approach or molecular orbital (MO) method is less intuitive to chemists but predicts spectroscopic properties better than the VB method.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] As opposed to VB theory, MO theory does not focus just the overlap of electron density in one area causing a bond but instead describes the whole molecule as one system.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] This leads to a more complex understanding of the system.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] This approach is the conceptual basis of the Hartree–Fock method and further post-Hartree–Fock methods.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] MO calculations result in orbitals or wavefunctions and energies for a molecule, which can be filled with electrons from two different atomic orbitals.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] These atomic orbitals come from separate atoms resulting in molecular orbitals being linear combinations of atomic orbitals.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] The Thomas–Fermi model was developed independently by Thomas and Fermi in 1927.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] This was the first attempt to describe many-electron systems on the basis of electronic density instead of wave functions, although it was not very successful in the treatment of entire molecules.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] The method did provide the basis for what is now known as density functional theory (DFT).
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] Modern day DFT uses the Kohn–Sham method, where the density functional is split into four terms; the Kohn–Sham kinetic energy, an external potential, exchange and correlation energies.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] A large part of the focus on developing DFT is on improving the exchange and correlation terms.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] Though this method is less developed than post Hartree–Fock methods, its significantly lower computational requirements (scaling typically no worse than *n*3 with respect to *n* basis functions, for the pure functionals) allow it to tackle larger polyatomic molecules and even macromolecules.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] This computational affordability and often comparable accuracy to MP2 and CCSD(T) (post-Hartree–Fock methods) has made it one of the most popular methods in computational chemistry.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] A further step can consist of solving the Schrödinger equation with the total molecular Hamiltonian in order to study the motion of molecules.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] Direct solution of the Schrödinger equation is called *quantum dynamics*, whereas its solution within the semiclassical approximation is called *semiclassical dynamics.* Purely classical simulations of molecular motion are referred to as *molecular dynamics (MD)*.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] Another approach to dynamics is a hybrid framework known as *mixed quantum-classical dynamics;* yet another hybrid framework uses the Feynman path integral formulation to add quantum corrections to molecular dynamics, which is called path integral molecular dynamics.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] Statistical approaches, using for example classical and quantum Monte Carlo methods, are also possible and are particularly useful for describing equilibrium distributions of states.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] In adiabatic dynamics, interatomic interactions are represented by single scalar potentials called potential energy surfaces.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] This is the Born–Oppenheimer approximation introduced by Born and Oppenheimer in 1927.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] Pioneering applications of this in chemistry were performed by Rice and Ramsperger in 1927 and Kassel in 1928, and generalized into the RRKM theory in 1952 by Marcus who took the transition state theory developed by Eyring in 1935 into account.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] These methods enable simple estimates of unimolecular reaction rates from a few characteristics of the potential surface.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] Non-adiabatic dynamics consists of taking the interaction between several coupled potential energy surfaces (corresponding to different electronic quantum states of the molecule).
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] The coupling terms are called vibronic couplings.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] The pioneering work in this field was done by Stueckelberg, Landau, and Zener in the 1930s, in their work on what is now known as the Landau–Zener transition.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] Their formula allows the transition probability between two adiabatic potential curves in the neighborhood of an avoided crossing to be calculated.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/electronic-structure] Spin-forbidden reactions are one type of non-adiabatic reactions where at least one change in spin state occurs when progressing from reactant to product.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] The MP perturbation theory is a special case of RS perturbation theory.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] Here, *λ* is an arbitrary real parameter that controls the size of the perturbation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] In MP theory the zeroth-order wave function is an exact eigenfunction of the Fock operator, which thus serves as the unperturbed operator.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] The perturbation is the correlation potential.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] Equating the factors of $\lambda ^{k}$ in this equation gives a *k*th-order perturbation equation, where *k* = 0, 1, 2, ..., *m*.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] See perturbation theory for more details.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] i.e. the zeroth-order energy is the expectation value of ${\hat {H}}$ with respect to Φ0, the Hartree-Fock energy.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] Hence, the first meaningful correction appears at MP2 energy.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] In order to obtain the MP2 formula for a closed-shell molecule, the second order RS-PT formula is written in a basis of doubly excited Slater determinants.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] (Singly excited Slater determinants do not contribute because of the Brillouin theorem).
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] where *𝜑**i* and *𝜑**j* are canonical occupied orbitals and *𝜑**a* and *𝜑**b* are virtual (or unoccupied) orbitals.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] The quantities *ε**i*, *ε**j*, *ε**a*, and *ε**b* are the corresponding orbital energies.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] Clearly, through second-order in the correlation potential, the total electronic energy is given by the Hartree–Fock energy plus second-order MP correction: *E* ≈ *E*HF + *E*MP2.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] The solution of the zeroth-order MP equation (which by definition is the Hartree–Fock equation) gives the Hartree–Fock energy.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] The first non-vanishing perturbation correction beyond the Hartree–Fock treatment is the second-order energy.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] Equivalent expressions are obtained by a slightly different partitioning of the Hamiltonian, which results in a different division of energy terms over zeroth- and first-order contributions, while for second- and higher-order energy corrections the two partitionings give identical results.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] The formulation is commonly used by chemists, who are now large users of these methods.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] (The Hartree–Fock energy is *not* equal to the sum of occupied-orbital energies).
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] Obviously, with this alternative formulation, the Møller–Plesset theorem does not hold in the literal sense that *E*MP1 ≠ 0.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] The solution of the zeroth-order MP equation is the sum of orbital energies.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] The zeroth plus first-order correction yields the Hartree–Fock energy.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] As with the original formulation, the first non-vanishing perturbation correction beyond the Hartree–Fock treatment is the second-order energy.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] To reiterate, the second- and higher-order corrections are the same in both formulations.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] Second (MP2), third (MP3), and fourth (MP4) order Møller–Plesset calculations are standard levels used in calculating small systems and are implemented in many computational chemistry codes.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] Higher level MP calculations, generally only MP5, are possible in some codes.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] However, they are rarely used because of their cost.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] Systematic studies of MP perturbation theory have shown that it is not necessarily a convergent theory at high orders.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] Convergence can be slow, rapid, oscillatory, regular, highly erratic or simply non-existent, depending on the precise chemical system or basis set.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] The density matrix for the first-order and higher MP2 wavefunction is of the type known as *response density*, which differs from the more usual *expectation value density*.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] The eigenvalues of the response density matrix (which are the occupation numbers of the MP2 natural orbitals) can therefore be greater than 2 or negative.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] Unphysical numbers are a sign of a divergent perturbation expansion.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] Additionally, various important molecular properties calculated at MP3 and MP4 level are no better than their MP2 counterparts, even for small molecules.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] For open shell molecules, MPn-theory can directly be applied only to unrestricted Hartree–Fock reference functions (since UHF states are not in general eigenvectors of the Fock operator).
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] However, the resulting energies often suffer from severe spin contamination, leading to large errors.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] A possible better alternative is to use one of the MP2-like methods based on restricted open-shell Hartree–Fock (ROHF).
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] There are many ROHF based MP2-like methods because of arbitrariness in the ROHF wavefunction(for example HCPT, ROMP, RMP (also called ROHF-MBPT2), OPT1 and OPT2, ZAPT, IOPT, etc.).
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] Some of the ROHF based MP2-like theories suffer from spin-contamination in their perturbed density and energies beyond second-order.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] These methods, Hartree–Fock, unrestricted Hartree–Fock and restricted Hartree–Fock use a single determinant wave function.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] MCSCF based methods are not without perturbation series divergences.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/møller-plesset-perturbation-theory] The analogue to what MP perturbation theory is in HF theory is Görling-Levy (GL) perturbation theory in Kohn-Sham (KS) density functional theory (DFT).
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/post-hartree-fock] In computational chemistry, **post–Hartree–Fock** (**post-HF**) methods are the set of methods developed to improve on the Hartree–Fock (HF), or self-consistent field (SCF), method.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/post-hartree-fock] They add electron correlation which is a more accurate way of including the repulsions between electrons than in the Hartree–Fock method where repulsions are only averaged.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/post-hartree-fock] For the great majority of systems under study, in particular for excited states and processes such as molecular dissociation reactions, the fourth item is by far the most important.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/post-hartree-fock] As a result, the term *post–Hartree–Fock method* is typically used for methods of approximating the electron correlation of a system.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/post-hartree-fock] Usually, post–Hartree–Fock methods give more accurate results than Hartree–Fock calculations, though at greater computational cost.
[src:quantum-chemistry-dft/post-hartree-fock] Methods that use more than one determinant are not strictly post–Hartree–Fock methods, as they use a single determinant as reference, but they often use similar perturbation, or configuration interaction methods to improve the description of electron correlation.
